04636nam a22007095i 9780801455742DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20152015nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979575377  a97808014557427 a10.7591/97808014557422doi  a(DE-B1597)478658  a(OCoLC)908552382  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aUB800b.W35 2016 7aPOL0120002bisacsh04a355.12962231 aWallace, Geoffrey P. R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLife and Death in Captivity :bThe Abuse of Prisoners during War /cGeoffrey P. R. Wallace. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (296 p.) :b1 map, 14 tables, 6 charts  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFigures and Tables -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Repertoires of Violence against Prisoners -- t2. The Captor’s Dilemma -- t3. Prisoners by the Numbers -- t4. World War II, Democracies, and the (Mis)Treatment of Prisoners -- t5. Territorial Conquest and the Katyn Massacre in Perspective -- tConclusion -- tAppendix. -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhy are prisoners horribly abused in some wars but humanely cared for in others? In Life and Death in Captivity, Geoffrey P. R. Wallace explores the profound differences in the ways captives are treated during armed conflict. Wallace focuses on the dual role played by regime type and the nature of the conflict in determining whether captor states opt for brutality or mercy. Integrating original data on prisoner treatment during the last century of interstate warfare with in-depth historical cases, Wallace demonstrates how domestic constraints and external incentives shape the fate of captured enemy combatants. Both Russia and Japan, for example, treated prisoners very differently in the Russo-Japanese War of 1904–5 and in World War II; the behavior of any given country is liable to vary from conflict to conflict and even within the same war.Democracies may be more likely to treat their captives humanely, yet this benevolence is rooted less in liberal norms of nonviolence than in concerns over public accountability. When such concerns are weak or absent, democracies are equally capable of brutal conduct toward captives. In conflicts that devolve into protracted fighting, belligerents may inflict violence against captives as part of a strategy of exploitation and to coerce the adversary into submission. When territory is at stake, prisoners are further at risk of cruel treatment as their captors seek to permanently remove the most threatening sources of opposition within newly conquered lands. By combining a rigorous strategic approach with a wide-ranging body of evidence, Wallace offers a vital contribution to the study of political violence and wartime conduct.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aPrisoners of warxAbuse of. 4aHistory. 4aMilitary History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Security (National & International).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060674440uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080145574240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801455742423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801455742/original  a978-3-11-060674-4  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK